Chapter 2: Documentation

Once you install Docusaurus, you can zero down on your documentation tasks. The docs folder contains all your documentation published on the Docusaurus site. You can add your document files to this folder.

Create Documentation From Scratchâ€‹

By default, Docusaurus supports Markdown files (files with a .md extension). Additionally, you can also use files with a .mdx extension (Markdown files with embedded JSX code). Markdown also supports some other file formats but not out of the box. You need to configure plugins to use such files. So, to put up your content on your Docusaurus site, you need to draft your content in Notepad++ or BBEdit (macOS) and save it as a .md file in the docs folder.

New to Markdown? Google Docs to the Rescueâ€‹

If you are not familiar with the Markdown syntax, you can just draft your content in Google Docs in plain English without worrying about the Markdown syntax. Google Docs provides you an option to download (or export) your document as a Markdown file. Just navigate to File > Download and select Markdown (.md).

However, when exporting files as Markdown, you need to take into account the following points.

  • Exporting numerous files as Markdown, could be time consuming since you must manually export each file.

  • You cannot use admonitions (callouts like Info, Warning, and so on) in Google Docs directly. However, Markdown supports admonitions. To include admonitions in your docs, you must manually create them once you export the docs to Markdown format. Click here to learn more about using admonitions in Markdown.

  • If you have code blocks in your Google Docs, post export Docusaurus does render them as a code block. However, the copy option which appears when users hover over the code snippet, is not displayed. Users must manually copy the code snippet. To make the copy option available, you must manually format code blocks. Click here to learn more about using admonitions in Markdown.

  • Google Docs supports collapsible sections only in pageless mode. However, these sections are not displayed in Docusaurus site even if they are used in Google Docs. You must manually enclose the collapsible content within the details tag as shown in the following syntax.

  <details>  
  <summary> Title </summary>  
  Content under the collapsible section.  
  </details>
note

The summary tag is optional. If you do not use it, the word details is displayed when the collapsible section is collapsed. If you use it, the word used within the summary tag is displayed when the section is collapsed (in this case, I have used the summary tag with the phrase Collapsible Section).

Using Existing Documentationâ€‹

If your documentation is already hosted on a portal and wish to test how your docs look in Docusaurus, you can export your docs project as Markdown. Most of the documentation tools provide an option to export your docs project in Markdown format. Even if Markdown export is not available, you can export your project in some other format like HTML, PDF, CHM, and so on, and then use AI tools to convert them to Markdown. Once your project is available in Markdown, you can move the files to the docs folder in the Docusaurus project.

Configure Sidebarâ€‹

Sidebar refers to the table of contents available on the left side of your documentation.

All the files present in the docs folder are listed in the sidebar. Files that are part of a folder are present under a collapsible section. In the above image, Tutorial - Basics is an example of a subfolder inside the docs folder. This is the auto-generated sidebar created by Docusaurus. You can overwrite it with your custom code to modify the look and feel.

Setting File and Folder Order In Sidebarâ€‹

Once you add your Markdown files in the docs folder, you can delete all the default files and folders created by Docusaurus. The process to set the order in which files and folders appear in the sidebar, is explained as follows.

Letâ€™s assume that you have the following document structure in the docs folder.

  1. Introduction (MarkDown file)

  2. Installation (MarkDown file)

  3. Create Record (MarkDown file)

  4. Advanced Topics (folder containing files)

To display the docs in the same order as mentioned above, you must perform the following tasks.

Setting Files Orderâ€‹

Add the frontmatter with the following syntax at the top of each Markdown file to control their order:


---

title: <file_title>

sidebar_position: <order>

---

So, the following code snippet must be inserted in the Introduction file.


---

title: Introduction

sidebar_position: 1

---

note
  • The name you enter in the title field appears on the sidebar, irrespective of the file name and title.
  • sidebar_position must be a unique number across all sibling docs/folders.

Similarly, you can add the code snippet to the remaining files by modifying the sidebar_position field's values to 2 for the Installation file and 3 for the Create Record file respectively.

Setting Folder Orderâ€‹

  • In case of folders, you must create a JSON file within the folder with the name _category_.json. Within this file, you must add the code snippet as shown below.

{

  "label": "Advanced Topics",

  "position": 4

}

  • The name you enter in the label field appears in the sidebar, irrespective of the folder name.

  • To set the order of files within a folder, you can follow the file order method.

  • Execute the npm run start command if you do not see the changes.

Versioningâ€‹

One of the many perks you get with Docusaurus is its ability to support documentation versioning. Versioning allows you to maintain multiple instances of your documentation. Each instance can represent a specific release cycle.

To implement versioning in your Docusaurus site, you need to make a couple of modifications to the code in the docusaurus.config.js file. The following sections explain the required changes.

Enable Versioningâ€‹

To enable the versioning feature in your Docusuaurs site:

  1. Open the docsuaurus.config.js file and locate the presets section.

  2. Under the presets section, locate the editUrl section.

  1. Add the following code snippet after the URL.

lastVersion: 'current',

 versions: {

  current: {

    label: 'Latest Version',

  },

},

note

  • While pasting the code ensure that the indentation requirements are met; the latestVersion and versions keys must be placed at the same level as editUrl. Basically, all the three keys must exist as siblings under the docs section and not nested within one another.

  • In the label field, I have used the word Latest Version. You can replace it with your desired name for the latest version. This name appears on the version drop-down menu.

Enable Version Drop-Down Menuâ€‹

Once you enable versioning, you must add a drop-down menu which allows users to switch between multiple versions of your documentation. To add the version drop-down menu, you need to make a couple of modifications to the code in the docusaurus.config.js file. The following steps explain the required changes.

  1. Locate navbar within the docusaurus.config.js file.

  2. Under navbar locate the items array.

  1. Under the items array add the following code snippet.

{

      type: 'docsVersionDropdown',

      position: 'right',

    },

  • To place the drop-down on the left side of the screen, you can use the word left in the position field.

Create Version Snapshotâ€‹

Once you enable versioning and create a drop-down menu to select versions, you must create a snapshot of your existing documentation and then run the build command.

  1. Execute the following command in your terminal.

npm run docusaurus docs: version old-version

  • Instead of old-version, you can use any other name that you wish to assign to your old-version. You can use numbers as well. For example, 1.0, 1.0.1, and so on.

  • This command creates a snapshot of all your existing documentation (that resides in the docs folder). This snapshot is stored under a new folder called old-version or whatever name/number you enter while executing the command.

  • You can make the changes to documentation in the docs folder. The content of files under the old-version folder are not affected. However, to modify content from the previous version, you must make changes to the files under the old-version.

  1. Execute the following command in your terminal to run the build.

npm run build

Create Multiple Versionsâ€‹

In the previous section, we saw how to enable versioning and create two versions of the documentation. In this section, we will go one step further and see how we can maintain multiple versions of docs.

Letâ€™s assume that you have two versions of documentation; 1.0 and 2.0. 2.0 is the latest version and 1.0 is the previous version. You wish to create a new version 3.0 and make version 2.0 also an old version, just like 1.0.

  1. Execute the following command in your terminal to create a snapshot of 2.0 version documentation.

npm run docusaurus docs: version 2.0

  1. In the docusaurus.config.js file, navigate to the version section.

  2. Replace 2.0 with 3.0 under the labels key.

  1. Execute the npm run build command in your terminal.
